# Initializations

Among the compiler options there is a TypeScript strict flag called `--strictPropertyInitialization`. When set to true, TypeScript will raise an error when a class property was declared but not set in the constructor.

This rule is not only a good practice for TypeScript class but also any kind of initialization. So initializing things is good.

This would be the criteria:

- Strings should be initialized to empty strings.
- Arrays should be initialized to empty arrays.
- Booleans should be initialized to `true` or `false`, at our convenience.
- Numbers should be initialized to `null` unless zero (`0`) value makes better sense.
- Objects should be initialized to `null` unless they are a global state (explained below).
- Map constructors should be initialized to empty maps as `new Map()`.
- Set constructors should be initialized to empty sets as `new Set()`.
- Dates should be initialized to `null` unless `new Date()` value makes better sense.
- We should never initialize to `undefined`.

When initializing states, the default value for an object would be `null` if we are setting a local/component state.

However, if we are setting a global/app state, then the object should be initialized property by property, by following the above criteria.
